{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-96d4083b7ea4a900", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tQuantum-Inspired Harmonic Decision Models: A\n2\tComputational Framework for Music Generation\n3\tJosef Pavlíček1, Petra Pavlíčková1, Martin Molhanec2\n4\t1\n5\t\n6\tCTU, Faculty of Information Technology, Thákurova 9, Prague 6, 160 00, Czech Republic\n7\t\n8\t2\n9\t\n10\tCTU, Faculty of Electrical Engineering, CTU, Technická 2, Prague 6, 160 00, Czech Republic\n11\t\n12\tABSTRACT\n13\t\n14\tThis paper introduces a quantum-inspired computational framework for harmonic decisionmaking in music. The proposed approach formulates harmonization as an optimization problem\n15\twithin a structured combinatorial space, where multiple candidate chord sequences are\n16\tevaluated under interacting musical constraints. The model combines an interference-based\n17\tharmonization stage with a classical optimization procedure grounded in tonal harmony. The\n18\tquantum-inspired component enables the parallel consideration of multiple harmonic\n19\talternatives, while the classical stage refines the resulting sequences to ensure structural\n20\tcoherence and stylistic plausibility.\n21\tThe framework is evaluated on selected musical examples, including Autumn Leaves and It’s\n22\ta Long Way to Tipperary. Quantitative analysis shows that the optimization stage significantly\n23\treduces chord density, increases harmonic stability, and improves functional organization. At\n24\tthe same time, expert evaluation highlights the importance of stylistic context, demonstrating\n25\tthat increased harmonic complexity is not always perceived as more natural. The results\n26\tsuggest that harmonic generation can be interpreted as a structured decision-making process in\n27\ta constrained search space. The proposed approach provides a computational model that\n28\tintegrates domain-specific knowledge with an interference-based search mechanism.\n29\tAlthough preliminary, this work indicates that quantum-inspired methods may offer a useful\n30\tframework for modeling complex decision processes in creative domains such as music. The\n31\tproposed framework contributes to ongoing research on quantum-inspired models of cognition\n32\tand decision-making in complex biological and creative systems.\n33\t\n34\tKeywords:\n35\t\n36\tquantum-inspired cognition, decision-making,\n37\tcomputational creativity, tonal harmony, optimization\n38\t\n39\tharmonic\n40\t\n41\tgeneration,\n42\t\n43\t1 Introduction\n44\tUnderstanding how humans generate structured creative decisions remains an open question\n45\t(Simon, 1972; Gigerenzer and Gaissmaier, 2011). This question spans multiple scientific\n46\tdisciplines, including cognitive science, artificial intelligence, neuroscience, and music theory\n47\t(Bharucha and Krumhansl, 1983). Musical composition provides a particularly suitable domain\n48\tfor investigating this problem, as it combines strict formal rules with a high degree of creative\n49\tfreedom (Krumhansl and Kessler, 1982). Composers operate within well-defined—though\n50\toften implicitly learned—theoretical frameworks such as tonal harmony, voice leading, and\n51\t\n52\t\ffunctional relationships between chords (Lerdahl and Jackendoff, 1983), yet the resulting\n53\tmusical structures often appear as spontaneous creative insights rather than deterministic\n54\toutputs of algorithmic procedures.\n55\tRecent advances in artificial intelligence have led to significant progress in automatic music\n56\tgeneration (Briot et al., 2019; Huang et al., 2018). Modern systems based on deep learning and\n57\tlarge-scale statistical models are capable of producing stylistically convincing musical outputs\n58\tby learning patterns from extensive datasets. However, these approaches primarily rely on\n59\tstatistical imitation and probabilistic prediction. In this sense, it remains an open question to\n60\twhat extent such predictions can be considered “intelligent” in a human decision-making sense.\n61\tAs a consequence, these models tend to reproduce stylistic regularities present in training data\n62\trather than explicitly modeling the structured decision processes underlying harmonic\n63\treasoning.\n64\tIn contrast, human composers navigate a complex space of possible harmonic structures while\n65\trespecting theoretical constraints such as tonal function, melodic compatibility, and stylistic\n66\tcoherence. This observation suggests that musical composition can be interpreted as a decision\n67\tprocess within a highly structured combinatorial space. Each melodic fragment can be\n68\tharmonized by many possible chord sequences; however, only a small subset satisfies musical\n69\tconstraints while simultaneously producing aesthetically convincing results.\n70\tImportantly, the notion of aesthetic value is not static but evolves over time. For example, the\n71\ttritone interval was historically considered undesirable in medieval music (“diabolus in\n72\tmusica”), whereas in contemporary music it is widely accepted and even characteristic of\n73\tcertain genres, such as heavy metal. This suggests that the evaluation of harmonic correctness\n74\tis context-dependent and influenced by style, historical development, and listener perception.\n75\tExploring such spaces efficiently therefore represents a non-trivial computational problem.\n76\tClassical optimization approaches, including rule-based systems and dynamic programming,\n77\tcan capture certain aspects of harmonic reasoning; however, they often require extensive\n78\theuristics to avoid combinatorial explosion.\n79\tIn recent years, quantum-inspired models have been proposed in various areas of cognition and\n80\tdecision-making (Khrennikov, 2010, 2017; Busemeyer and Bruza, 2012). These models do not\n81\tassume that biological systems perform physical quantum computation. Instead, they employ\n82\tmathematical structures derived from quantum theory—such as superposition, interference,\n83\tand probabilistic amplitude dynamics—to describe complex decision processes. Such\n84\tapproaches have proven useful in modeling context-dependent decision-making, ambiguity\n85\tresolution, and preference shifts.\n86\tMotivated by these approaches, this work investigates a quantum-inspired computational\n87\tframework for harmonic decision-making in music. The central idea is to formulate the\n88\tselection of harmonic progressions as an optimization problem within a structured space of\n89\tchord configurations. Instead of relying on purely deterministic search, the proposed model\n90\temploys an interference-based mechanism inspired by the Quantum Approximate\n91\tOptimization Algorithm (QAOA), enabling parallel evaluation of multiple harmonic\n92\tcandidates.\n93\tThe proposed framework consists of two complementary components. First, a quantuminspired harmonization stage generates candidate chord structures through interference-based\n94\t\n95\t\fexploration of a discrete harmonic state space. Second, a classical optimization stage refines\n96\tthese candidates using established principles of tonal harmony, including functional\n97\trelationships, chord inversions, and voice-leading constraints. This hybrid architecture\n98\tintegrates structured musical knowledge with an efficient search mechanism.\n99\tBeyond music generation, the proposed model can be interpreted as an experimental platform\n100\tfor studying structured decision-making processes in creative cognition. By analyzing\n101\tharmonizations generated under different optimization strategies, it becomes possible to\n102\tinvestigate whether interference-based search mechanisms provide advantages over classical\n103\tapproaches when navigating complex creative spaces.\n104\tThe remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section 2 introduces the theoretical\n105\tbackground. Section 3 formalizes the harmonic search space. Section 4 presents the quantuminspired harmonization algorithm. Section 5 describes the classical optimization stage. Section\n106\t6 provides experimental evaluation. Finally, Section 7 discusses implications for computational\n107\tcreativity and decision-making.\n108\t\n109\t2 Background\n110\tThis section introduces the theoretical foundations underlying the proposed approach. We first\n111\toutline tonal harmony as a structured system of constraints, then discuss decision-making in\n112\tcomplex combinatorial spaces, and finally review relevant concepts from quantum-inspired\n113\tmodels of cognition.\n114\t\n115\t2.1 Tonal Harmony as a Constraint System\n116\tTonal harmony can be understood as a structured system of constraints governing the\n117\trelationships between musical elements. Within this framework, chords are not independent\n118\tentities but are organized according to functional roles, such as tonic, dominant, and\n119\tsubdominant. These roles define expectations and permissible transitions, forming a network\n120\tof dependencies that guides harmonic progression.\n121\tIn addition to functional relationships, harmonic structures are constrained by voice-leading\n122\tprinciples, which impose local continuity conditions on individual melodic lines. These\n123\tconstraints limit abrupt changes and favor smooth transitions between successive chords. As a\n124\tresult, the space of possible harmonizations for a given melody is highly structured but nontrivial.\n125\tImportantly, this system does not uniquely determine a single solution. Multiple harmonic\n126\trealizations may satisfy the same set of constraints while differing in stylistic or expressive\n127\tqualities. This inherent multiplicity suggests that harmonic composition involves selecting\n128\tamong competing alternatives rather than deriving a single deterministic outcome.\n129\t\n130\t2.2 Decision-Making in Structured Spaces\n131\t\n132\t\fThe process of selecting harmonic progressions can be interpreted as decision-making within\n133\ta structured combinatorial space. Each candidate solution corresponds to a sequence of chords\n134\tthat must satisfy multiple interacting constraints, including tonal function, melodic\n135\tcompatibility, and stylistic coherence.\n136\tSuch spaces are typically characterized by a large number of possible configurations, most of\n137\twhich violate one or more constraints. Identifying valid and musically meaningful solutions\n138\ttherefore requires efficient exploration strategies. Classical approaches to this problem often\n139\trely on rule-based systems, heuristic search, or optimization techniques such as dynamic\n140\tprogramming.\n141\tHowever, these methods face limitations when dealing with highly complex or contextdependent decision spaces. In particular, they may struggle to balance competing constraints\n142\tor to capture the flexibility observed in human creative behavior. This has motivated the\n143\texploration of alternative computational paradigms capable of representing and navigating\n144\tsuch spaces more effectively.\n145\t\n146\t2.3 Quantum-Inspired Models of Cognition\n147\tQuantum-inspired models of cognition provide a mathematical framework for describing\n148\tdecision-making processes that deviate from classical probabilistic reasoning (Khrennikov,\n149\t2010, 2013; Busemeyer and Bruza, 2012). Rather than assuming that decisions arise from fixed\n150\tprobability distributions, these models represent cognitive states as superpositions of multiple\n151\tpotential outcomes.\n152\tWithin this framework, the act of decision-making can be interpreted as a transformation of\n153\tthese states, where interference effects influence the likelihood of particular outcomes. This\n154\tallows the model to capture context-dependent behavior, ambiguity resolution, and nonclassical probability patterns observed in empirical studies. Similar approaches have also been\n155\texplored in the context of biological and cognitive systems, where quantum-like models have\n156\tbeen used to describe decision processes under uncertainty and contextual influence (Asano et\n157\tal., 2011).\n158\tImportantly, the use of quantum formalism in this context does not imply that cognitive\n159\tprocesses are physically quantum. Instead, it provides a flexible mathematical language for\n160\tmodeling complex systems in which multiple competing possibilities coexist and interact.\n161\tThese properties make quantum-inspired approaches particularly relevant for domains such as\n162\tmusical harmony, where multiple valid solutions exist and must be evaluated under interacting\n163\tconstraints.\n164\t\n165\t3 Harmonic Search Space\n166\tIn this section, we formalize harmonic generation as a search process within a structured space\n167\tof chord configurations. The goal is to define the elements of this space, their formal\n168\trepresentation, and the constraints that govern valid harmonic solutions.\n169\t\n170\t\fThe proposed formulation builds on established formal approaches to harmony, where chords\n171\tare represented as structured sets of pitch classes and constructed through interval-based\n172\ttransformations.\n173\t\n174\t3.1 Melody Representation\n175\tLet M = (m₁, m₂, ..., m_T) denote a melodic sequence of length T, where each element m_t\n176\trepresents a pitch event at time step t.\n177\tWe define the pitch space as the set of pitch classes modulo 12:\n178\t𝓟 = ℤ₁₂ = {0, 1, ..., 11}\n179\twhere each melodic element m_t ∈ 𝓟 (or a higher-level representation such as MIDI pitch\n180\tmapped to pitch class).\n181\tFor the purposes of harmonic generation, the melody defines a sequence of anchor points that\n182\tconstrain the selection of compatible chords. At each time step t, the corresponding harmonic\n183\tchoice must be consistent with the melodic note m_t, either by containing it as a chord tone or\n184\tby supporting it as a non-chord tone under standard harmonic conventions.\n185\t\n186\t3.2 Chord Candidate Space\n187\tLet C_t denote the set of candidate chords available at time step t.\n188\tEach chord c ∈ C_t is represented as a finite subset of pitch classes:\n189\tc ⊆ 𝓟.\n190\tIn addition to its pitch-class content, each chord carries structural attributes such as chord\n191\tquality (e.g., major, minor, dominant seventh) and inversion.\n192\tChord construction can be interpreted as the application of interval-based transformations to a\n193\troot pitch. Formally, given a root r ∈ 𝓟, a chord can be constructed as:\n194\tc = {r, r + Δ₁, r + Δ₂, ...} mod 12,\n195\twhere Δ_i represent interval offsets (e.g., major third, perfect fifth, minor seventh).\n196\tThe global harmonic configuration is defined as a sequence:\n197\tC = (c₁, c₂, ..., c_T),\n198\twhere c_t ∈ C_t for each time step t.\n199\t\n200\t\fThe size of the search space grows exponentially with T, as the total number of possible\n201\tharmonic sequences is given by the Cartesian product:\n202\t|C₁ × C₂ × ... × C_T|.\n203\tThis combinatorial growth makes exhaustive search impractical even for relatively short\n204\tmelodies, motivating the need for structured search strategies.\n205\t\n206\t3.3 Constraint System\n207\tThe set of valid harmonic sequences is restricted by a system of constraints reflecting principles\n208\tof tonal harmony. These constraints define a structured subspace of musically plausible\n209\tsolutions.\n210\tThey can be divided into three main categories:\n211\t(i) Functional constraints:\n212\tChord progressions should follow plausible functional relationships, such as transitions\n213\tbetween tonic, dominant, and subdominant regions.\n214\t(ii) Melodic compatibility constraints:\n215\tEach chord c_t must be compatible with the corresponding melodic element m_t, ensuring that\n216\tthe melody is harmonically supported.\n217\t(iii) Voice-leading constraints:\n218\tTransitions between consecutive chords (c_t, c_{t+1}) should minimize abrupt changes and\n219\tfavor smooth movement between individual voices.\n220\tThese constraints significantly reduce the effective search space; however, even within this\n221\trestricted subset, multiple competing harmonic configurations typically exist.\n222\tTherefore, harmonic generation can be formulated as an optimization problem over a\n223\tconstrained combinatorial space, where the objective is to identify sequences that best satisfy\n224\ta weighted combination of these criteria.\n225\t\n226\t4 Quantum-Inspired Harmonizer\n227\tIn this section, we introduce a quantum-inspired approach to harmonic generation, formulated\n228\tas a structured search process over the combinatorial space defined in Section 3.\n229\tThe proposed method does not assume that physical quantum processes are involved in musical\n230\tcognition. Instead, it adopts mathematical principles inspired by quantum theory—particularly\n231\tsuperposition and interference—to guide the exploration of multiple harmonic candidates in\n232\tparallel.\n233\t\n234\t\f4.1 Superposition of Harmonic Candidates\n235\tAt each time step t, instead of selecting a single chord c_t ∈ C_t deterministically, we consider\n236\ta weighted representation over multiple candidates.\n237\tThis can be interpreted as a superposition-like state over the candidate set:\n238\tψ_t = ∑_{c ∈ C_t} w(c) · |c⟩,\n239\twhere w(c) represents a weight associated with chord candidate c, and |c⟩ denotes an abstract\n240\trepresentation of that chord.\n241\tUnlike physical quantum states, these weights do not need to satisfy strict normalization\n242\tconstraints; rather, they serve as a flexible mechanism for representing competing harmonic\n243\thypotheses.\n244\t\n245\t4.2 Interference-Based Evaluation\n246\tThe key idea of the proposed model is that harmonic candidates are not evaluated\n247\tindependently. Instead, their contributions interact through an interference-like mechanism that\n248\treflects how different constraints reinforce or suppress specific harmonic configurations.\n249\tEach candidate chord c is assigned a score based on multiple criteria:\n250\t•\n251\t•\n252\t•\n253\t\n254\tmelodic compatibility,\n255\tfunctional coherence,\n256\tvoice-leading smoothness.\n257\t\n258\tThese criteria can be combined into a global evaluation function:\n259\tE(c₁, c₂, ..., c_T),\n260\twhich assigns a scalar value to a complete harmonic sequence.\n261\tRather than evaluating each sequence independently, the model iteratively adjusts candidate\n262\tweights such that harmonically consistent configurations are reinforced, while inconsistent\n263\tones are suppressed. This process is conceptually analogous to constructive and destructive\n264\tinterference.\n265\t\n266\t4.3 Iterative Refinement Process\n267\tThe harmonization process proceeds iteratively.\n268\tStarting from an initial distribution of candidate chords at each time step, the model repeatedly\n269\tupdates the weights w(c) based on their contribution to globally coherent harmonic sequences.\n270\t\n271\t\fAt each iteration, the following steps are performed (Figure 1):\n272\t•\n273\t•\n274\t•\n275\t\n276\tGenerate candidate combinations of chords across time steps.\n277\tEvaluate these combinations using a global constraint-based scoring function E, which\n278\tquantifies their melodic compatibility, functional coherence, and voice-leading\n279\tsmoothness.\n280\tUpdate the weights w(c) to favour candidates that participate in higher-scoring\n281\tconfigurations.\n282\t\n283\tFigure 1. Quantum harmonic optimization flowchart (source: Author)\n284\tThis iterative refinement gradually concentrates the search toward a subset of harmonically\n285\tconsistent solutions.\n286\t\n287\t4.4 Relation to Approximate Optimization\n288\tThe proposed approach can be interpreted as a heuristic approximation to combinatorial\n289\toptimization methods. In particular, it shares conceptual similarities with algorithms that\n290\titeratively refine candidate solutions using feedback from a global objective function.\n291\tWhile inspired by the Quantum Approximate Optimization Algorithm (QAOA), the present\n292\tmodel remains entirely classical in its implementation. The reference to quantum-inspired\n293\tmechanisms serves primarily as a conceptual framework for understanding how multiple\n294\tcandidate solutions can be explored and selectively amplified.\n295\t\n296\t5 Hybrid Classical Optimization\n297\tWhile the quantum-inspired harmonization stage provides a mechanism for exploring the space\n298\tof possible harmonic configurations, the resulting candidates may still contain local\n299\tinconsistencies or suboptimal transitions.\n300\t\n301\t\fTo address this, we introduce a subsequent classical optimization stage that refines the\n302\tharmonic sequence using established principles of tonal harmony.\n303\tThis hybrid approach combines exploratory search with rule-based correction, allowing the\n304\tsystem to balance global coherence with local musical correctness.\n305\t\n306\t5.1 Harmonic Smoothing\n307\tThe first refinement step focuses on harmonic smoothing, aiming to eliminate abrupt or\n308\tstylistically implausible transitions between consecutive chords.\n309\tGiven a sequence C = (c₁, c₂, ..., c_T), we evaluate each pair (c_t, c_{t+1}) and apply local\n310\tadjustments where necessary. These adjustments may include:\n311\t- replacing a chord with a functionally related alternative,\n312\t- inserting intermediate chords to improve continuity,\n313\t- resolving unstable harmonic movements.\n314\tThis process improves the overall flow of the harmonic progression while preserving\n315\tcompatibility with the melody.\n316\t\n317\t5.2 Inversion Selection\n318\tNext, chord inversions are selected to optimize voice leading and reduce large pitch movements\n319\tbetween successive chords.\n320\tFor each chord c_t, multiple inversion variants are considered. The selection criterion\n321\tprioritizes:\n322\t- minimal total voice displacement,\n323\t- avoidance of parallel motion where stylistically inappropriate,\n324\t- preservation of chord identity and function.\n325\tThis step transforms abstract chord representations into more realistic harmonic realizations.\n326\t\n327\t5.3 Cadence Stabilization\n328\tThe final refinement stage addresses cadence stabilization, ensuring that the harmonic\n329\tsequence exhibits structurally meaningful points of resolution.\n330\tParticular attention is given to phrase endings, where standard cadential patterns (e.g.,\n331\tdominant–tonic resolution) are preferred.\n332\tIf necessary, the model adjusts the final chords in a segment to reinforce a sense of closure,\n333\twhile maintaining consistency with preceding harmonic context.\n334\t\n335\t\f5.4 Integration with the Search Process\n336\tThe classical optimization stage operates as a post-processing layer applied to the output of the\n337\tquantum-inspired harmonizer.\n338\tImportantly, this stage does not replace the exploratory mechanism, but complements it. The\n339\tharmonizer is responsible for navigating the global search space, while the classical optimizer\n340\tenforces local consistency and stylistic correctness.\n341\tTogether, these components form a hybrid architecture that integrates structured musical\n342\tknowledge with an efficient search strategy over complex combinatorial spaces.\n343\t\n344\t6 Experiments and Illustrative Evaluation\n345\tThe aim of the experimental section is not to provide a large-scale benchmark, but rather to\n346\tillustrate how the proposed framework behaves on concrete musical examples and whether its\n347\toutputs exhibit musically plausible decision patterns.\n348\tTwo types of harmonic outputs were considered:\n349\t• the direct output of the quantum-inspired harmonizer,\n350\t• the refined output after classical optimization.\n351\t• All outputs were generated from the same input melody and exported as MusicXML\n352\tfor inspection and comparison.\n353\t\n354\t\fFigure 2. Tipperary 9 beats– raw vs optimized harmonization (source: Author)\n355\t\n356\tFigure 3. Autumn Leaves 8 beats – raw vs optimized harmonization (source: Author)\n357\tThe generated harmonisations for both musical examples are illustrated in Figures 2 and 3.\n358\tEach figure shows a comparison between the raw harmonizer output and the optimized version.\n359\t\n360\t\fThese examples provide a qualitative reference for interpreting the quantitative metrics\n361\tpresented in the following sections.\n362\t\n363\t6.1 Evaluation Metrics\n364\tThe generated harmonizations were evaluated using a combination of structural and expertbased criteria. Structurally, we considered melodic compatibility, functional coherence, and\n365\tthe density of harmonic changes. Melodic compatibility was defined as the proportion of time\n366\tsteps at which the melody note was contained in the corresponding chord. Functional coherence\n367\twas assessed in terms of plausibility of transitions between tonic, subdominant, and dominant\n368\tregions. In addition, the number of chord changes was used as a simple measure of harmonic\n369\tstability versus fragmentation.\n370\tTo complement these structural measures, the resulting harmonizations were also assessed\n371\tqualitatively by a professional musician, who evaluated the outputs with respect to harmonic\n372\tnaturalness, stylistic plausibility, and the perceived quality of cadential resolution.\n373\tIn addition to qualitative expert evaluation, several quantitative indicators were computed to\n374\tcharacterize the generated harmonizations.\n375\tThese include:\n376\t•\n377\t•\n378\t•\n379\t•\n380\t\n381\tChord density (average number of chord changes per measure)\n382\tChord complexity (ratio of extended chords, e.g., seventh chords, to triads)\n383\tMelodic coverage (percentage of melody notes contained in the corresponding chord)\n384\tHarmonic stability (average duration of chord persistence)\n385\t\n386\t6.2 Quantitative Analysis\n387\tTo complement the qualitative evaluation, several quantitative indicators were computed for\n388\tboth the raw harmonizer output and the optimized version.\n389\tTable 1 summarizes the chord density, defined as the average number of chord changes per\n390\tmeasure. The optimization stage leads to a substantial reduction in chord density for both\n391\tevaluated melodies. In the case of Autumn Leaves, chord density decreases from 4.00 to 2.71\n392\tchanges per measure, while for It’s a Long Way to Tipperary it decreases from 4.00 to 2.53.\n393\tThis corresponds to a reduction of 1.29 and 1.47 chord changes per measure, respectively,\n394\tindicating a significant decrease in harmonic fragmentation.\n395\tTable 1. Chord density and reduction after optimization.\n396\tSong\n397\tAutumn\n398\tLeaves\n399\tIt's a Long Way\n400\tto Tipperary\n401\t\n402\tRaw Density\n403\t\n404\tOptimized Density\n405\t\n406\tReduction\n407\t\n408\t4,00\n409\t\n410\t2,71\n411\t\n412\t1,29\n413\t\n414\t4,00\n415\t\n416\t2,53\n417\t\n418\t1,47\n419\t\n420\tAt the same time, chord duration increases notably. As shown in Table 3, the average chord\n421\tduration nearly doubles in the optimized version (from 1.00 to 1.87 for Autumn Leaves and\n422\t\n423\t\ffrom 1.00 to 1.98 for Tipperary), suggesting improved harmonic stability and smoother\n424\tstructural flow.\n425\tChord density (Table 1) further reflects this effect. While the raw harmonizer assigns chords\n426\tat a high temporal resolution (often one chord per beat, primarily for technical and analytical\n427\tpurposes), the optimizer reduces the number of chord changes (from 4.00 to 2.71 for Autumn\n428\tLeaves and from 4.00 to 2.53 for Tipperary), effectively simplifying the harmonic structure\n429\tand extending chord durations.\n430\tThe complexity of harmonic structures was assessed using the ratio of extended chords (e.g.,\n431\tseventh chords). The results (Table 2) indicate that the raw harmonizer produces a consistently\n432\thigh proportion of extended chords (up to 100%), whereas the optimized version reduces this\n433\tratio (to 77.6% and 74.4%). This reflects a shift toward a more balanced harmonic vocabulary,\n434\tcloser to stylistically plausible practice.\n435\tMelodic coverage, defined as the proportion of melody notes contained in the corresponding\n436\tchord, shows a moderate decrease after optimization (e.g., from 96.2% to 84.6% for Autumn\n437\tLeaves). This suggests that the optimizer allows for a more flexible harmonic interpretation,\n438\tincluding non-chord tones and passing tones, rather than enforcing strict chord-tone alignment.\n439\tThe distribution of harmonic functions (Table 2) reveals additional structural changes. While\n440\tthe raw harmonizer tends to favor tonic-related chords, the optimized version reduces their\n441\tproportion (e.g., from 61.6% to 52.8% in Autumn Leaves) and increases the presence of\n442\tdominant functions (from 21.4% to 23.2%). In Tipperary, dominant usage increases more\n443\tsubstantially (from 14.7% to 23.5%). This indicates that the optimizer introduces greater\n444\tharmonic tension and directional movement within the progression.\n445\tFinally, the average bass movement between consecutive chords was reduced (Δ = 0.56 for\n446\tAutumn Leaves and Δ = 0.72 for Tipperary), indicating improved voice-leading smoothness\n447\tand fewer abrupt transitions.\n448\tOverall, the quantitative analysis confirms that the classical optimization stage systematically\n449\treduces harmonic fragmentation, increases structural stability, and introduces a more balanced\n450\tfunctional distribution, while maintaining acceptable melodic compatibility.\n451\tTable 2. Harmonic structure metrics.\n452\tVariant\n453\tAutumn Raw\n454\tAutumn Opt\n455\tTipperary Raw\n456\tTipperary Opt\n457\t\n458\tT\n459\t61,6%\n460\t52,8%\n461\t73,5%\n462\t67,1%\n463\t\n464\tS\n465\t17,0%\n466\t16,2%\n467\t11,8%\n468\t8,2%\n469\t\n470\tD\n471\t21,4%\n472\t23,2%\n473\t14,7%\n474\t23,5%\n475\t\n476\tOther\n477\t0,0%\n478\t7,7%\n479\t0,0%\n480\t1,2%\n481\t\n482\tTable 3. Harmonic stability and bass movement.\n483\tSong\n484\tAutumn Leaves\n485\tIt's a Long Way to\n486\tTipperary\n487\t\n488\tRaw Avg\n489\tDuration\n490\t1,00\n491\t\n492\tOptimized Avg\n493\tDuration\n494\t1,87\n495\t\n496\t0,56\n497\t\n498\t1,00\n499\t\n500\t1,98\n501\t\n502\t0,72\n503\t\n504\tRaw vs Opt Bass Jump Δ\n505\t\n506\t\f6.3 Interpretation and Expert Evaluation\n507\tThe quantitative findings are partially supported by a qualitative evaluation involving two\n508\tprofessional musicians and six non-expert listeners. While the sample size is limited, the\n509\tevaluation provides initial insight into the perceived quality of the generated harmonizations.\n510\tFor Autumn Leaves, the optimized version was consistently perceived as more coherent and\n511\tstructurally convincing than the raw harmonizer output. In particular, improvements were\n512\tnoted in cadential resolution and overall harmonic organization.\n513\tIn contrast, for It’s a Long Way to Tipperary, the expert evaluation revealed a different pattern.\n514\tWhile the optimized version exhibited improved structural properties according to quantitative\n515\tmetrics, it was perceived as less natural in some respects, particularly due to increased\n516\tharmonic complexity and less intuitive bass movement.\n517\tThis divergence suggests that the effectiveness of the optimization stage depends on the\n518\tstylistic characteristics of the input melody. For harmonically rich jazz standards such as\n519\tAutumn Leaves, increased structural complexity may enhance musical plausibility. However,\n520\tfor simpler, more diatonic melodies such as Tipperary, excessive harmonic elaboration may\n521\treduce perceived naturalness.\n522\tThese findings highlight an important aspect of harmonic decision-making: optimal solutions\n523\tare context-dependent and cannot be fully captured by structural metrics alone. The interaction\n524\tbetween harmonic complexity, stylistic expectations, and perceptual coherence plays a crucial\n525\trole in evaluating generated harmonizations. One of the professional evaluators noted that at\n526\tstructurally important points of the melody, particularly at local peaks, harmonization should\n527\temphasize stronger functional roles. In this context, dominant chords were consistently\n528\tperceived as providing stronger support than alternative harmonizations based on weaker\n529\tfunctions (e.g., mediant), even when alternative solutions were theoretically valid.\n530\t\n531\t7 Discussion\n532\tThe proposed framework introduces a quantum-inspired perspective on harmonic generation,\n533\tinterpreting the process as decision-making within a structured combinatorial space. Rather\n534\tthan treating harmonization as purely statistical sequence prediction, the model explicitly\n535\tincorporates constraints derived from tonal harmony and explores their interaction through an\n536\tinterference-based search mechanism.\n537\tThe experimental results suggest that this hybrid approach captures several important aspects\n538\tof human-like harmonic reasoning. In particular, the reduction of chord density and the increase\n539\tin harmonic stability indicate that the classical optimization stage effectively refines the\n540\texploratory output of the harmonizer into more coherent structures. At the same time, the\n541\tquantum-inspired stage enables the simultaneous consideration of multiple harmonic\n542\talternatives, which is difficult to achieve using purely deterministic or greedy methods.\n543\tFrom the perspective of cognitive modeling, the framework aligns with the view that human\n544\tdecision-making does not operate as a strictly sequential or deterministic process. Instead,\n545\t\n546\t\fmultiple competing alternatives may coexist and be evaluated in parallel, with contextdependent factors influencing the final selection. The use of superposition-like representations\n547\tand interference-inspired evaluation provides a computational analogy for such processes,\n548\twithout assuming any underlying physical quantum mechanisms. Such interpretations are\n549\tconsistent with broader efforts to apply quantum-theoretic formalisms to complex systems and\n550\tcognition (Kitto, 2008; Khrennikov, 2013).\n551\tThe observed differences between musical examples further highlight the context-dependent\n552\tnature of harmonic decision-making. While the optimized harmonization improved perceived\n553\tcoherence in harmonically rich material (Autumn Leaves), it was less effective for simpler\n554\tmelodic structures (Tipperary). This suggests that the balance between harmonic complexity\n555\tand perceptual clarity is not universal, but depends on stylistic and structural characteristics of\n556\tthe musical input. Such variability is consistent with findings in cognitive science, where\n557\tdecision strategies adapt to the structure of the problem space (Gigerenzer and Gaissmaier,\n558\t2011).\n559\tImportantly, the proposed model should be understood as a computational abstraction rather\n560\tthan a claim about biological implementation. The term “quantum-inspired” refers here to the\n561\tuse of mathematical principles—such as parallel representation of alternatives and\n562\tinterference-like evaluation—rather than to physical quantum processes in the brain. This\n563\tdistinction is crucial for maintaining conceptual clarity and scientific validity.\n564\tBeyond music generation, the framework may have broader implications for modeling\n565\tdecision-making in other structured creative domains. Problems involving multiple competing\n566\tsolutions under complex constraints—such as design, language generation, or planning—may\n567\tbenefit from similar hybrid approaches combining exploratory search with structured\n568\trefinement.\n569\tAt the same time, the present study has several limitations. The experimental evaluation is\n570\tlimited in scale and relies on a small number of musical examples and expert assessments.\n571\tFuture work should extend the evaluation to larger datasets, incorporate multiple expert\n572\tevaluators, and explore more systematic comparisons with existing algorithmic approaches.\n573\tDespite these limitations, the results indicate that interference-based search mechanisms\n574\tprovide a promising direction for modeling structured decision processes in creative domains.\n575\tThe integration of such mechanisms with domain-specific knowledge may offer a useful\n576\tframework for bridging computational modeling and cognitive theories of decision-making.\n577\tAn important limitation of the present study concerns the use of well-known musical material.\n578\tBoth evaluated melodies (Autumn Leaves and It’s a Long Way to Tipperary) are widely\n579\trecognized, which may influence subjective evaluation. Expert and non-expert listeners are\n580\tlikely to be biased by their prior knowledge of the original harmonic structure, which affects\n581\ttheir perception of alternative harmonizations.\n582\tThis effect was explicitly noted by one of the professional evaluators, who emphasized that\n583\teven when attempting to ignore the original harmony, expectations remain influenced by\n584\tlearned musical patterns. In particular, it was observed that structurally strong harmonic\n585\tfunctions (such as the dominant) are preferred at key melodic peaks, as they provide greater\n586\tperceived support than weaker alternatives (e.g., mediant-based harmonizations).\n587\t\n588\t\fTo reduce such bias and improve objectivity, future work should include experiments with\n589\tnewly composed or previously unknown melodies. This would allow evaluation of the\n590\tproposed model in a setting where listeners are not influenced by prior exposure, and would\n591\tenable a clearer assessment of harmonic plausibility across both expert and non-expert groups.\n592\tFurthermore, the present evaluation involved a limited number of participants, including two\n593\texpert musicians and a small group of non-expert listeners. While the results provide initial\n594\tinsights, larger-scale studies are needed to establish statistically robust conclusions.\n595\t\n596\t8 Conclusion\n597\tThis paper presented a quantum-inspired computational framework for harmonic decisionmaking in music. The proposed approach formulates harmonization as an optimization problem\n598\twithin a structured combinatorial space, where multiple candidate solutions are explored and\n599\tevaluated under interacting constraints.\n600\tThe framework combines two complementary components: an interference-based\n601\tharmonization stage that generates candidate chord sequences, and a classical optimization\n602\tstage that refines these candidates using established principles of tonal harmony. This hybrid\n603\tarchitecture allows the model to balance exploratory search with structural coherence.\n604\tExperimental results demonstrate that the optimization stage systematically improves\n605\tharmonic stability, reduces fragmentation, and produces more structured chord progressions.\n606\tAt the same time, the qualitative evaluation highlights the importance of stylistic context,\n607\tshowing that increased harmonic complexity is not universally beneficial and must be aligned\n608\twith the character of the input melody.\n609\tFrom a broader perspective, the proposed model contributes to the understanding of creative\n610\tdecision-making as a process of navigating structured spaces of alternatives. The use of\n611\tquantum-inspired concepts provides a flexible computational framework for representing and\n612\tevaluating multiple competing solutions without relying on purely deterministic strategies.\n613\tAlthough preliminary, the results suggest that interference-based search mechanisms, when\n614\tcombined with domain-specific knowledge, may offer a promising direction for modeling\n615\tcomplex decision processes in both music and other creative domains.\n616\tFuture work will focus on extending the evaluation to larger datasets, incorporating multiple\n617\texpert assessments, and exploring the applicability of the proposed framework to other forms\n618\tof structured creative generation.\n619\tThe implementation and evaluation data are publicly available to support reproducibility.\n620\t\n621\tData availability statement\n622\tThe data and code supporting the findings of this study are available in a public repository at:\n623\t[https://github.com/JosefPavlicek/quantum-harmonic-decision-model.git].\n624\t\n625\t\fReferences\n626\t1. Simon, H. A. (1972) Theories of bounded rationality. In: McGuire, C. B. and Radner,\n627\tR. (eds.) Decision and Organization. Amsterdam: North-Holland, pp. 161–176.\n628\t2. Lerdahl, F. and Jackendoff, R. (1983) A Generative Theory of Tonal Music.\n629\tCambridge, MA: MIT Press. Available at:\n630\thttps://books.google.cz/books?id=6HGiEW33lucC [accessed 22 March 2026].\n631\t3. Gigerenzer, G. and Gaissmaier, W. (2011) Heuristic decision making. Annual\n632\tReview of Psychology, 62, pp. 451–482.\n633\thttps://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-psych-120709-145346\n634\t4. Bharucha, J. J. and Krumhansl, C. L. (1983)\n635\tThe representation of harmonic structure in music: Hierarchies of stability as a\n636\tfunction of context. Cognition, 13(1), pp. 63–102.\n637\thttps://doi.org/10.1016/0010-0277(83)90003-3\n638\t5. Krumhansl, C. L. and Kessler, E. J. (1982)\n639\tTracing the dynamic changes in perceived tonal organization in a spatial\n640\trepresentation of musical keys. Psychological Review, 89(4), pp. 334–368.\n641\thttps://doi.org/10.1037/0033-295X.89.4.334\n642\t6. Briot, J.-P., Hadjeres, G., & Pachet, F.-D. (2019). Deep Learning Techniques for\n643\tMusic Generation—A Survey. https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1709.01620\n644\t7. Huang, C.-Z. A. et al. (2018) Music Transformer: Generating music with long-term\n645\tstructure. arXiv preprint arXiv:1809.04281.\n646\thttps://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1809.04281\n647\t8. Khrennikov, A. (2010). Ubiquitous Quantum Structure: From Psychology to Finance.\n648\tBerlin: Springer. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-05101-2\n649\t9. Khrennikov, A. (2013). Quantum-like model of cognitive decision making and\n650\tinformation processing. BioSystems, 112(2), 95–103.\n651\thttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.biosystems.2013.02.002\n652\t10. Khrennikov, A. (2017). Why Quantum? In: Haven, E., Khrennikov, A. (eds) The\n653\tPalgrave Handbook of Quantum Models in Social Science. Palgrave Macmillan,\n654\tLondon. https://doi.org/10.1057/978-1-137-49276-0_15\n655\t11. Busemeyer, J. R. and Bruza, P. D. (2012) Quantum Models of Cognition and\n656\tDecision.\n657\tCambridge: Cambridge University Press.\n658\thttps://doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511997716\n659\t12. Pothos, E. M. and Busemeyer, J. R. (2009)\n660\tA quantum probability explanation for violations of ‘rational’ decision theory.\n661\tProceedings of the Royal Society B, 276(1665), pp. 2171–2178.\n662\thttps://doi.org/10.1098/rspb.2009.0121\n663\t13. Asano, M., Ohya, M., Tanaka, Y., Basieva, I. a Khrennikov, A. (2011). Quantum-like\n664\tmodel of brain's functioning: Decision making from decoherence. Journal of\n665\tTheoretical Biology, 281(1), s. 56–64. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jtbi.2011.04.022\n666\t14. Kitto, K. (2008). Why Quantum Theory. Available at:\n667\thttps://api.semanticscholar.org/CorpusID:118817897\n668\t\n669\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f933fe3f-c9df-45b5-88b5-3abbab6f62c3", "uuid": "d48a3dfa-eb21-4a63-8004-6e250e4dde0e", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T05:49:57.371Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.05007.txt", "content": "Quantum-Inspired Harmonic Decision Models: A\nComputational Framework for Music Generation\nJosef Pavlíček1, Petra Pavlíčková1, Martin Molhanec2\n1\n\nCTU, Faculty of Information Technology, Thákurova 9, Prague 6, 160 00, Czech Republic\n\n2\n\nCTU, Faculty of Electrical Engineering, CTU, Technická 2, Prague 6, 160 00, Czech Republic\n\nABSTRACT\n\nThis paper introduces a quantum-inspired computational framework for harmonic decisionmaking in music. The proposed approach formulates harmonization as an optimization problem\nwithin a structured combinatorial space, where multiple candidate chord sequences are\nevaluated under interacting musical constraints. The model combines an interference-based\nharmonization stage with a classical optimization procedure grounded in tonal harmony. The\nquantum-inspired component enables the parallel consideration of multiple harmonic\nalternatives, while the classical stage refines the resulting sequences to ensure structural\ncoherence and stylistic plausibility.\nThe framework is evaluated on selected musical examples, including Autumn Leaves and It’s\na Long Way to Tipperary. Quantitative analysis shows that the optimization stage significantly\nreduces chord density, increases harmonic stability, and improves functional organization. At\nthe same time, expert evaluation highlights the importance of stylistic context, demonstrating\nthat increased harmonic complexity is not always perceived as more natural. The results\nsuggest that harmonic generation can be interpreted as a structured decision-making process in\na constrained search space. The proposed approach provides a computational model that\nintegrates domain-specific knowledge with an interference-based search mechanism.\nAlthough preliminary, this work indicates that quantum-inspired methods may offer a useful\nframework for modeling complex decision processes in creative domains such as music. The\nproposed framework contributes to ongoing research on quantum-inspired models of cognition\nand decision-making in complex biological and creative systems.\n\nKeywords:\n\nquantum-inspired cognition, decision-making,\ncomputational creativity, tonal harmony, optimization\n\nharmonic\n\ngeneration,\n\n1 Introduction\nUnderstanding how humans generate structured creative decisions remains an open question\n(Simon, 1972; Gigerenzer and Gaissmaier, 2011). This question spans multiple scientific\ndisciplines, including cognitive science, artificial intelligence, neuroscience, and music theory\n(Bharucha and Krumhansl, 1983). Musical composition provides a particularly suitable domain\nfor investigating this problem, as it combines strict formal rules with a high degree of creative\nfreedom (Krumhansl and Kessler, 1982). Composers operate within well-defined—though\noften implicitly learned—theoretical frameworks such as tonal harmony, voice leading, and\n\n\ffunctional relationships between chords (Lerdahl and Jackendoff, 1983), yet the resulting\nmusical structures often appear as spontaneous creative insights rather than deterministic\noutputs of algorithmic procedures.\nRecent advances in artificial intelligence have led to significant progress in automatic music\ngeneration (Briot et al., 2019; Huang et al., 2018). Modern systems based on deep learning and\nlarge-scale statistical models are capable of producing stylistically convincing musical outputs\nby learning patterns from extensive datasets. However, these approaches primarily rely on\nstatistical imitation and probabilistic prediction. In this sense, it remains an open question to\nwhat extent such predictions can be considered “intelligent” in a human decision-making sense.\nAs a consequence, these models tend to reproduce stylistic regularities present in training data\nrather than explicitly modeling the structured decision processes underlying harmonic\nreasoning.\nIn contrast, human composers navigate a complex space of possible harmonic structures while\nrespecting theoretical constraints such as tonal function, melodic compatibility, and stylistic\ncoherence. This observation suggests that musical composition can be interpreted as a decision\nprocess within a highly structured combinatorial space. Each melodic fragment can be\nharmonized by many possible chord sequences; however, only a small subset satisfies musical\nconstraints while simultaneously producing aesthetically convincing results.\nImportantly, the notion of aesthetic value is not static but evolves over time. For example, the\ntritone interval was historically considered undesirable in medieval music (“diabolus in\nmusica”), whereas in contemporary music it is widely accepted and even characteristic of\ncertain genres, such as heavy metal. This suggests that the evaluation of harmonic correctness\nis context-dependent and influenced by style, historical development, and listener perception.\nExploring such spaces efficiently therefore represents a non-trivial computational problem.\nClassical optimization approaches, including rule-based systems and dynamic programming,\ncan capture certain aspects of harmonic reasoning; however, they often require extensive\nheuristics to avoid combinatorial explosion.\nIn recent years, quantum-inspired models have been proposed in various areas of cognition and\ndecision-making (Khrennikov, 2010, 2017; Busemeyer and Bruza, 2012). These models do not\nassume that biological systems perform physical quantum computation. Instead, they employ\nmathematical structures derived from quantum theory—such as superposition, interference,\nand probabilistic amplitude dynamics—to describe complex decision processes. Such\napproaches have proven useful in modeling context-dependent decision-making, ambiguity\nresolution, and preference shifts.\nMotivated by these approaches, this work investigates a quantum-inspired computational\nframework for harmonic decision-making in music. The central idea is to formulate the\nselection of harmonic progressions as an optimization problem within a structured space of\nchord configurations. Instead of relying on purely deterministic search, the proposed model\nemploys an interference-based mechanism inspired by the Quantum Approximate\nOptimization Algorithm (QAOA), enabling parallel evaluation of multiple harmonic\ncandidates.\nThe proposed framework consists of two complementary components. First, a quantuminspired harmonization stage generates candidate chord structures through interference-based\n\n\fexploration of a discrete harmonic state space. Second, a classical optimization stage refines\nthese candidates using established principles of tonal harmony, including functional\nrelationships, chord inversions, and voice-leading constraints. This hybrid architecture\nintegrates structured musical knowledge with an efficient search mechanism.\nBeyond music generation, the proposed model can be interpreted as an experimental platform\nfor studying structured decision-making processes in creative cognition. By analyzing\nharmonizations generated under different optimization strategies, it becomes possible to\ninvestigate whether interference-based search mechanisms provide advantages over classical\napproaches when navigating complex creative spaces.\nThe remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section 2 introduces the theoretical\nbackground. Section 3 formalizes the harmonic search space. Section 4 presents the quantuminspired harmonization algorithm. Section 5 describes the classical optimization stage. Section\n6 provides experimental evaluation. Finally, Section 7 discusses implications for computational\ncreativity and decision-making.\n\n2 Background\nThis section introduces the theoretical foundations underlying the proposed approach. We first\noutline tonal harmony as a structured system of constraints, then discuss decision-making in\ncomplex combinatorial spaces, and finally review relevant concepts from quantum-inspired\nmodels of cognition.\n\n2.1 Tonal Harmony as a Constraint System\nTonal harmony can be understood as a structured system of constraints governing the\nrelationships between musical elements. Within this framework, chords are not independent\nentities but are organized according to functional roles, such as tonic, dominant, and\nsubdominant. These roles define expectations and permissible transitions, forming a network\nof dependencies that guides harmonic progression.\nIn addition to functional relationships, harmonic structures are constrained by voice-leading\nprinciples, which impose local continuity conditions on individual melodic lines. These\nconstraints limit abrupt changes and favor smooth transitions between successive chords. As a\nresult, the space of possible harmonizations for a given melody is highly structured but nontrivial.\nImportantly, this system does not uniquely determine a single solution. Multiple harmonic\nrealizations may satisfy the same set of constraints while differing in stylistic or expressive\nqualities. This inherent multiplicity suggests that harmonic composition involves selecting\namong competing alternatives rather than deriving a single deterministic outcome.\n\n2.2 Decision-Making in Structured Spaces\n\n\fThe process of selecting harmonic progressions can be interpreted as decision-making within\na structured combinatorial space. Each candidate solution corresponds to a sequence of chords\nthat must satisfy multiple interacting constraints, including tonal function, melodic\ncompatibility, and stylistic coherence.\nSuch spaces are typically characterized by a large number of possible configurations, most of\nwhich violate one or more constraints. Identifying valid and musically meaningful solutions\ntherefore requires efficient exploration strategies. Classical approaches to this problem often\nrely on rule-based systems, heuristic search, or optimization techniques such as dynamic\nprogramming.\nHowever, these methods face limitations when dealing with highly complex or contextdependent decision spaces. In particular, they may struggle to balance competing constraints\nor to capture the flexibility observed in human creative behavior. This has motivated the\nexploration of alternative computational paradigms capable of representing and navigating\nsuch spaces more effectively.\n\n2.3 Quantum-Inspired Models of Cognition\nQuantum-inspired models of cognition provide a mathematical framework for describing\ndecision-making processes that deviate from classical probabilistic reasoning (Khrennikov,\n2010, 2013; Busemeyer and Bruza, 2012). Rather than assuming that decisions arise from fixed\nprobability distributions, these models represent cognitive states as superpositions of multiple\npotential outcomes.\nWithin this framework, the act of decision-making can be interpreted as a transformation of\nthese states, where interference effects influence the likelihood of particular outcomes. This\nallows the model to capture context-dependent behavior, ambiguity resolution, and nonclassical probability patterns observed in empirical studies. Similar approaches have also been\nexplored in the context of biological and cognitive systems, where quantum-like models have\nbeen used to describe decision processes under uncertainty and contextual influence (Asano et\nal., 2011).\nImportantly, the use of quantum formalism in this context does not imply that cognitive\nprocesses are physically quantum. Instead, it provides a flexible mathematical language for\nmodeling complex systems in which multiple competing possibilities coexist and interact.\nThese properties make quantum-inspired approaches particularly relevant for domains such as\nmusical harmony, where multiple valid solutions exist and must be evaluated under interacting\nconstraints.\n\n3 Harmonic Search Space\nIn this section, we formalize harmonic generation as a search process within a structured space\nof chord configurations. The goal is to define the elements of this space, their formal\nrepresentation, and the constraints that govern valid harmonic solutions.\n\n\fThe proposed formulation builds on established formal approaches to harmony, where chords\nare represented as structured sets of pitch classes and constructed through interval-based\ntransformations.\n\n3.1 Melody Representation\nLet M = (m₁, m₂, ..., m_T) denote a melodic sequence of length T, where each element m_t\nrepresents a pitch event at time step t.\nWe define the pitch space as the set of pitch classes modulo 12:\n𝓟 = ℤ₁₂ = {0, 1, ..., 11}\nwhere each melodic element m_t ∈ 𝓟 (or a higher-level representation such as MIDI pitch\nmapped to pitch class).\nFor the purposes of harmonic generation, the melody defines a sequence of anchor points that\nconstrain the selection of compatible chords. At each time step t, the corresponding harmonic\nchoice must be consistent with the melodic note m_t, either by containing it as a chord tone or\nby supporting it as a non-chord tone under standard harmonic conventions.\n\n3.2 Chord Candidate Space\nLet C_t denote the set of candidate chords available at time step t.\nEach chord c ∈ C_t is represented as a finite subset of pitch classes:\nc ⊆ 𝓟.\nIn addition to its pitch-class content, each chord carries structural attributes such as chord\nquality (e.g., major, minor, dominant seventh) and inversion.\nChord construction can be interpreted as the application of interval-based transformations to a\nroot pitch. Formally, given a root r ∈ 𝓟, a chord can be constructed as:\nc = {r, r + Δ₁, r + Δ₂, ...} mod 12,\nwhere Δ_i represent interval offsets (e.g., major third, perfect fifth, minor seventh).\nThe global harmonic configuration is defined as a sequence:\nC = (c₁, c₂, ..., c_T),\nwhere c_t ∈ C_t for each time step t.\n\n\fThe size of the search space grows exponentially with T, as the total number of possible\nharmonic sequences is given by the Cartesian product:\n|C₁ × C₂ × ... × C_T|.\nThis combinatorial growth makes exhaustive search impractical even for relatively short\nmelodies, motivating the need for structured search strategies.\n\n3.3 Constraint System\nThe set of valid harmonic sequences is restricted by a system of constraints reflecting principles\nof tonal harmony. These constraints define a structured subspace of musically plausible\nsolutions.\nThey can be divided into three main categories:\n(i) Functional constraints:\nChord progressions should follow plausible functional relationships, such as transitions\nbetween tonic, dominant, and subdominant regions.\n(ii) Melodic compatibility constraints:\nEach chord c_t must be compatible with the corresponding melodic element m_t, ensuring that\nthe melody is harmonically supported.\n(iii) Voice-leading constraints:\nTransitions between consecutive chords (c_t, c_{t+1}) should minimize abrupt changes and\nfavor smooth movement between individual voices.\nThese constraints significantly reduce the effective search space; however, even within this\nrestricted subset, multiple competing harmonic configurations typically exist.\nTherefore, harmonic generation can be formulated as an optimization problem over a\nconstrained combinatorial space, where the objective is to identify sequences that best satisfy\na weighted combination of these criteria.\n\n4 Quantum-Inspired Harmonizer\nIn this section, we introduce a quantum-inspired approach to harmonic generation, formulated\nas a structured search process over the combinatorial space defined in Section 3.\nThe proposed method does not assume that physical quantum processes are involved in musical\ncognition. Instead, it adopts mathematical principles inspired by quantum theory—particularly\nsuperposition and interference—to guide the exploration of multiple harmonic candidates in\nparallel.\n\n\f4.1 Superposition of Harmonic Candidates\nAt each time step t, instead of selecting a single chord c_t ∈ C_t deterministically, we consider\na weighted representation over multiple candidates.\nThis can be interpreted as a superposition-like state over the candidate set:\nψ_t = ∑_{c ∈ C_t} w(c) · |c⟩,\nwhere w(c) represents a weight associated with chord candidate c, and |c⟩ denotes an abstract\nrepresentation of that chord.\nUnlike physical quantum states, these weights do not need to satisfy strict normalization\nconstraints; rather, they serve as a flexible mechanism for representing competing harmonic\nhypotheses.\n\n4.2 Interference-Based Evaluation\nThe key idea of the proposed model is that harmonic candidates are not evaluated\nindependently. Instead, their contributions interact through an interference-like mechanism that\nreflects how different constraints reinforce or suppress specific harmonic configurations.\nEach candidate chord c is assigned a score based on multiple criteria:\n•\n•\n•\n\nmelodic compatibility,\nfunctional coherence,\nvoice-leading smoothness.\n\nThese criteria can be combined into a global evaluation function:\nE(c₁, c₂, ..., c_T),\nwhich assigns a scalar value to a complete harmonic sequence.\nRather than evaluating each sequence independently, the model iteratively adjusts candidate\nweights such that harmonically consistent configurations are reinforced, while inconsistent\nones are suppressed. This process is conceptually analogous to constructive and destructive\ninterference.\n\n4.3 Iterative Refinement Process\nThe harmonization process proceeds iteratively.\nStarting from an initial distribution of candidate chords at each time step, the model repeatedly\nupdates the weights w(c) based on their contribution to globally coherent harmonic sequences.\n\n\fAt each iteration, the following steps are performed (Figure 1):\n•\n•\n•\n\nGenerate candidate combinations of chords across time steps.\nEvaluate these combinations using a global constraint-based scoring function E, which\nquantifies their melodic compatibility, functional coherence, and voice-leading\nsmoothness.\nUpdate the weights w(c) to favour candidates that participate in higher-scoring\nconfigurations.\n\nFigure 1. Quantum harmonic optimization flowchart (source: Author)\nThis iterative refinement gradually concentrates the search toward a subset of harmonically\nconsistent solutions.\n\n4.4 Relation to Approximate Optimization\nThe proposed approach can be interpreted as a heuristic approximation to combinatorial\noptimization methods. In particular, it shares conceptual similarities with algorithms that\niteratively refine candidate solutions using feedback from a global objective function.\nWhile inspired by the Quantum Approximate Optimization Algorithm (QAOA), the present\nmodel remains entirely classical in its implementation. The reference to quantum-inspired\nmechanisms serves primarily as a conceptual framework for understanding how multiple\ncandidate solutions can be explored and selectively amplified.\n\n5 Hybrid Classical Optimization\nWhile the quantum-inspired harmonization stage provides a mechanism for exploring the space\nof possible harmonic configurations, the resulting candidates may still contain local\ninconsistencies or suboptimal transitions.\n\n\fTo address this, we introduce a subsequent classical optimization stage that refines the\nharmonic sequence using established principles of tonal harmony.\nThis hybrid approach combines exploratory search with rule-based correction, allowing the\nsystem to balance global coherence with local musical correctness.\n\n5.1 Harmonic Smoothing\nThe first refinement step focuses on harmonic smoothing, aiming to eliminate abrupt or\nstylistically implausible transitions between consecutive chords.\nGiven a sequence C = (c₁, c₂, ..., c_T), we evaluate each pair (c_t, c_{t+1}) and apply local\nadjustments where necessary. These adjustments may include:\n- replacing a chord with a functionally related alternative,\n- inserting intermediate chords to improve continuity,\n- resolving unstable harmonic movements.\nThis process improves the overall flow of the harmonic progression while preserving\ncompatibility with the melody.\n\n5.2 Inversion Selection\nNext, chord inversions are selected to optimize voice leading and reduce large pitch movements\nbetween successive chords.\nFor each chord c_t, multiple inversion variants are considered. The selection criterion\nprioritizes:\n- minimal total voice displacement,\n- avoidance of parallel motion where stylistically inappropriate,\n- preservation of chord identity and function.\nThis step transforms abstract chord representations into more realistic harmonic realizations.\n\n5.3 Cadence Stabilization\nThe final refinement stage addresses cadence stabilization, ensuring that the harmonic\nsequence exhibits structurally meaningful points of resolution.\nParticular attention is given to phrase endings, where standard cadential patterns (e.g.,\ndominant–tonic resolution) are preferred.\nIf necessary, the model adjusts the final chords in a segment to reinforce a sense of closure,\nwhile maintaining consistency with preceding harmonic context.\n\n\f5.4 Integration with the Search Process\nThe classical optimization stage operates as a post-processing layer applied to the output of the\nquantum-inspired harmonizer.\nImportantly, this stage does not replace the exploratory mechanism, but complements it. The\nharmonizer is responsible for navigating the global search space, while the classical optimizer\nenforces local consistency and stylistic correctness.\nTogether, these components form a hybrid architecture that integrates structured musical\nknowledge with an efficient search strategy over complex combinatorial spaces.\n\n6 Experiments and Illustrative Evaluation\nThe aim of the experimental section is not to provide a large-scale benchmark, but rather to\nillustrate how the proposed framework behaves on concrete musical examples and whether its\noutputs exhibit musically plausible decision patterns.\nTwo types of harmonic outputs were considered:\n• the direct output of the quantum-inspired harmonizer,\n• the refined output after classical optimization.\n• All outputs were generated from the same input melody and exported as MusicXML\nfor inspection and comparison.\n\n\fFigure 2. Tipperary 9 beats– raw vs optimized harmonization (source: Author)\n\nFigure 3. Autumn Leaves 8 beats – raw vs optimized harmonization (source: Author)\nThe generated harmonisations for both musical examples are illustrated in Figures 2 and 3.\nEach figure shows a comparison between the raw harmonizer output and the optimized version.\n\n\fThese examples provide a qualitative reference for interpreting the quantitative metrics\npresented in the following sections.\n\n6.1 Evaluation Metrics\nThe generated harmonizations were evaluated using a combination of structural and expertbased criteria. Structurally, we considered melodic compatibility, functional coherence, and\nthe density of harmonic changes. Melodic compatibility was defined as the proportion of time\nsteps at which the melody note was contained in the corresponding chord. Functional coherence\nwas assessed in terms of plausibility of transitions between tonic, subdominant, and dominant\nregions. In addition, the number of chord changes was used as a simple measure of harmonic\nstability versus fragmentation.\nTo complement these structural measures, the resulting harmonizations were also assessed\nqualitatively by a professional musician, who evaluated the outputs with respect to harmonic\nnaturalness, stylistic plausibility, and the perceived quality of cadential resolution.\nIn addition to qualitative expert evaluation, several quantitative indicators were computed to\ncharacterize the generated harmonizations.\nThese include:\n•\n•\n•\n•\n\nChord density (average number of chord changes per measure)\nChord complexity (ratio of extended chords, e.g., seventh chords, to triads)\nMelodic coverage (percentage of melody notes contained in the corresponding chord)\nHarmonic stability (average duration of chord persistence)\n\n6.2 Quantitative Analysis\nTo complement the qualitative evaluation, several quantitative indicators were computed for\nboth the raw harmonizer output and the optimized version.\nTable 1 summarizes the chord density, defined as the average number of chord changes per\nmeasure. The optimization stage leads to a substantial reduction in chord density for both\nevaluated melodies. In the case of Autumn Leaves, chord density decreases from 4.00 to 2.71\nchanges per measure, while for It’s a Long Way to Tipperary it decreases from 4.00 to 2.53.\nThis corresponds to a reduction of 1.29 and 1.47 chord changes per measure, respectively,\nindicating a significant decrease in harmonic fragmentation.\nTable 1. Chord density and reduction after optimization.\nSong\nAutumn\nLeaves\nIt's a Long Way\nto Tipperary\n\nRaw Density\n\nOptimized Density\n\nReduction\n\n4,00\n\n2,71\n\n1,29\n\n4,00\n\n2,53\n\n1,47\n\nAt the same time, chord duration increases notably. As shown in Table 3, the average chord\nduration nearly doubles in the optimized version (from 1.00 to 1.87 for Autumn Leaves and\n\n\ffrom 1.00 to 1.98 for Tipperary), suggesting improved harmonic stability and smoother\nstructural flow.\nChord density (Table 1) further reflects this effect. While the raw harmonizer assigns chords\nat a high temporal resolution (often one chord per beat, primarily for technical and analytical\npurposes), the optimizer reduces the number of chord changes (from 4.00 to 2.71 for Autumn\nLeaves and from 4.00 to 2.53 for Tipperary), effectively simplifying the harmonic structure\nand extending chord durations.\nThe complexity of harmonic structures was assessed using the ratio of extended chords (e.g.,\nseventh chords). The results (Table 2) indicate that the raw harmonizer produces a consistently\nhigh proportion of extended chords (up to 100%), whereas the optimized version reduces this\nratio (to 77.6% and 74.4%). This reflects a shift toward a more balanced harmonic vocabulary,\ncloser to stylistically plausible practice.\nMelodic coverage, defined as the proportion of melody notes contained in the corresponding\nchord, shows a moderate decrease after optimization (e.g., from 96.2% to 84.6% for Autumn\nLeaves). This suggests that the optimizer allows for a more flexible harmonic interpretation,\nincluding non-chord tones and passing tones, rather than enforcing strict chord-tone alignment.\nThe distribution of harmonic functions (Table 2) reveals additional structural changes. While\nthe raw harmonizer tends to favor tonic-related chords, the optimized version reduces their\nproportion (e.g., from 61.6% to 52.8% in Autumn Leaves) and increases the presence of\ndominant functions (from 21.4% to 23.2%). In Tipperary, dominant usage increases more\nsubstantially (from 14.7% to 23.5%). This indicates that the optimizer introduces greater\nharmonic tension and directional movement within the progression.\nFinally, the average bass movement between consecutive chords was reduced (Δ = 0.56 for\nAutumn Leaves and Δ = 0.72 for Tipperary), indicating improved voice-leading smoothness\nand fewer abrupt transitions.\nOverall, the quantitative analysis confirms that the classical optimization stage systematically\nreduces harmonic fragmentation, increases structural stability, and introduces a more balanced\nfunctional distribution, while maintaining acceptable melodic compatibility.\nTable 2. Harmonic structure metrics.\nVariant\nAutumn Raw\nAutumn Opt\nTipperary Raw\nTipperary Opt\n\nT\n61,6%\n52,8%\n73,5%\n67,1%\n\nS\n17,0%\n16,2%\n11,8%\n8,2%\n\nD\n21,4%\n23,2%\n14,7%\n23,5%\n\nOther\n0,0%\n7,7%\n0,0%\n1,2%\n\nTable 3. Harmonic stability and bass movement.\nSong\nAutumn Leaves\nIt's a Long Way to\nTipperary\n\nRaw Avg\nDuration\n1,00\n\nOptimized Avg\nDuration\n1,87\n\n0,56\n\n1,00\n\n1,98\n\n0,72\n\nRaw vs Opt Bass Jump Δ\n\n\f6.3 Interpretation and Expert Evaluation\nThe quantitative findings are partially supported by a qualitative evaluation involving two\nprofessional musicians and six non-expert listeners. While the sample size is limited, the\nevaluation provides initial insight into the perceived quality of the generated harmonizations.\nFor Autumn Leaves, the optimized version was consistently perceived as more coherent and\nstructurally convincing than the raw harmonizer output. In particular, improvements were\nnoted in cadential resolution and overall harmonic organization.\nIn contrast, for It’s a Long Way to Tipperary, the expert evaluation revealed a different pattern.\nWhile the optimized version exhibited improved structural properties according to quantitative\nmetrics, it was perceived as less natural in some respects, particularly due to increased\nharmonic complexity and less intuitive bass movement.\nThis divergence suggests that the effectiveness of the optimization stage depends on the\nstylistic characteristics of the input melody. For harmonically rich jazz standards such as\nAutumn Leaves, increased structural complexity may enhance musical plausibility. However,\nfor simpler, more diatonic melodies such as Tipperary, excessive harmonic elaboration may\nreduce perceived naturalness.\nThese findings highlight an important aspect of harmonic decision-making: optimal solutions\nare context-dependent and cannot be fully captured by structural metrics alone. The interaction\nbetween harmonic complexity, stylistic expectations, and perceptual coherence plays a crucial\nrole in evaluating generated harmonizations. One of the professional evaluators noted that at\nstructurally important points of the melody, particularly at local peaks, harmonization should\nemphasize stronger functional roles. In this context, dominant chords were consistently\nperceived as providing stronger support than alternative harmonizations based on weaker\nfunctions (e.g., mediant), even when alternative solutions were theoretically valid.\n\n7 Discussion\nThe proposed framework introduces a quantum-inspired perspective on harmonic generation,\ninterpreting the process as decision-making within a structured combinatorial space. Rather\nthan treating harmonization as purely statistical sequence prediction, the model explicitly\nincorporates constraints derived from tonal harmony and explores their interaction through an\ninterference-based search mechanism.\nThe experimental results suggest that this hybrid approach captures several important aspects\nof human-like harmonic reasoning. In particular, the reduction of chord density and the increase\nin harmonic stability indicate that the classical optimization stage effectively refines the\nexploratory output of the harmonizer into more coherent structures. At the same time, the\nquantum-inspired stage enables the simultaneous consideration of multiple harmonic\nalternatives, which is difficult to achieve using purely deterministic or greedy methods.\nFrom the perspective of cognitive modeling, the framework aligns with the view that human\ndecision-making does not operate as a strictly sequential or deterministic process. Instead,\n\n\fmultiple competing alternatives may coexist and be evaluated in parallel, with contextdependent factors influencing the final selection. The use of superposition-like representations\nand interference-inspired evaluation provides a computational analogy for such processes,\nwithout assuming any underlying physical quantum mechanisms. Such interpretations are\nconsistent with broader efforts to apply quantum-theoretic formalisms to complex systems and\ncognition (Kitto, 2008; Khrennikov, 2013).\nThe observed differences between musical examples further highlight the context-dependent\nnature of harmonic decision-making. While the optimized harmonization improved perceived\ncoherence in harmonically rich material (Autumn Leaves), it was less effective for simpler\nmelodic structures (Tipperary). This suggests that the balance between harmonic complexity\nand perceptual clarity is not universal, but depends on stylistic and structural characteristics of\nthe musical input. Such variability is consistent with findings in cognitive science, where\ndecision strategies adapt to the structure of the problem space (Gigerenzer and Gaissmaier,\n2011).\nImportantly, the proposed model should be understood as a computational abstraction rather\nthan a claim about biological implementation. The term “quantum-inspired” refers here to the\nuse of mathematical principles—such as parallel representation of alternatives and\ninterference-like evaluation—rather than to physical quantum processes in the brain. This\ndistinction is crucial for maintaining conceptual clarity and scientific validity.\nBeyond music generation, the framework may have broader implications for modeling\ndecision-making in other structured creative domains. Problems involving multiple competing\nsolutions under complex constraints—such as design, language generation, or planning—may\nbenefit from similar hybrid approaches combining exploratory search with structured\nrefinement.\nAt the same time, the present study has several limitations. The experimental evaluation is\nlimited in scale and relies on a small number of musical examples and expert assessments.\nFuture work should extend the evaluation to larger datasets, incorporate multiple expert\nevaluators, and explore more systematic comparisons with existing algorithmic approaches.\nDespite these limitations, the results indicate that interference-based search mechanisms\nprovide a promising direction for modeling structured decision processes in creative domains.\nThe integration of such mechanisms with domain-specific knowledge may offer a useful\nframework for bridging computational modeling and cognitive theories of decision-making.\nAn important limitation of the present study concerns the use of well-known musical material.\nBoth evaluated melodies (Autumn Leaves and It’s a Long Way to Tipperary) are widely\nrecognized, which may influence subjective evaluation. Expert and non-expert listeners are\nlikely to be biased by their prior knowledge of the original harmonic structure, which affects\ntheir perception of alternative harmonizations.\nThis effect was explicitly noted by one of the professional evaluators, who emphasized that\neven when attempting to ignore the original harmony, expectations remain influenced by\nlearned musical patterns. In particular, it was observed that structurally strong harmonic\nfunctions (such as the dominant) are preferred at key melodic peaks, as they provide greater\nperceived support than weaker alternatives (e.g., mediant-based harmonizations).\n\n\fTo reduce such bias and improve objectivity, future work should include experiments with\nnewly composed or previously unknown melodies. This would allow evaluation of the\nproposed model in a setting where listeners are not influenced by prior exposure, and would\nenable a clearer assessment of harmonic plausibility across both expert and non-expert groups.\nFurthermore, the present evaluation involved a limited number of participants, including two\nexpert musicians and a small group of non-expert listeners. While the results provide initial\ninsights, larger-scale studies are needed to establish statistically robust conclusions.\n\n8 Conclusion\nThis paper presented a quantum-inspired computational framework for harmonic decisionmaking in music. The proposed approach formulates harmonization as an optimization problem\nwithin a structured combinatorial space, where multiple candidate solutions are explored and\nevaluated under interacting constraints.\nThe framework combines two complementary components: an interference-based\nharmonization stage that generates candidate chord sequences, and a classical optimization\nstage that refines these candidates using established principles of tonal harmony. This hybrid\narchitecture allows the model to balance exploratory search with structural coherence.\nExperimental results demonstrate that the optimization stage systematically improves\nharmonic stability, reduces fragmentation, and produces more structured chord progressions.\nAt the same time, the qualitative evaluation highlights the importance of stylistic context,\nshowing that increased harmonic complexity is not universally beneficial and must be aligned\nwith the character of the input melody.\nFrom a broader perspective, the proposed model contributes to the understanding of creative\ndecision-making as a process of navigating structured spaces of alternatives. The use of\nquantum-inspired concepts provides a flexible computational framework for representing and\nevaluating multiple competing solutions without relying on purely deterministic strategies.\nAlthough preliminary, the results suggest that interference-based search mechanisms, when\ncombined with domain-specific knowledge, may offer a promising direction for modeling\ncomplex decision processes in both music and other creative domains.\nFuture work will focus on extending the evaluation to larger datasets, incorporating multiple\nexpert assessments, and exploring the applicability of the proposed framework to other forms\nof structured creative generation.\nThe implementation and evaluation data are publicly available to support reproducibility.\n\nData availability statement\nThe data and code supporting the findings of this study are available in a public repository at:\n[https://github.com/JosefPavlicek/quantum-harmonic-decision-model.git].\n\n\fReferences\n1. Simon, H. A. (1972) Theories of bounded rationality. In: McGuire, C. B. and Radner,\nR. (eds.) Decision and Organization. Amsterdam: North-Holland, pp. 161–176.\n2. Lerdahl, F. and Jackendoff, R. (1983) A Generative Theory of Tonal Music.\nCambridge, MA: MIT Press. Available at:\nhttps://books.google.cz/books?id=6HGiEW33lucC [accessed 22 March 2026].\n3. Gigerenzer, G. and Gaissmaier, W. (2011) Heuristic decision making. Annual\nReview of Psychology, 62, pp. 451–482.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-psych-120709-145346\n4. Bharucha, J. J. and Krumhansl, C. L. (1983)\nThe representation of harmonic structure in music: Hierarchies of stability as a\nfunction of context. Cognition, 13(1), pp. 63–102.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/0010-0277(83)90003-3\n5. Krumhansl, C. L. and Kessler, E. J. (1982)\nTracing the dynamic changes in perceived tonal organization in a spatial\nrepresentation of musical keys. Psychological Review, 89(4), pp. 334–368.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1037/0033-295X.89.4.334\n6. Briot, J.-P., Hadjeres, G., & Pachet, F.-D. (2019). Deep Learning Techniques for\nMusic Generation—A Survey. https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1709.01620\n7. Huang, C.-Z. A. et al. (2018) Music Transformer: Generating music with long-term\nstructure. arXiv preprint arXiv:1809.04281.\nhttps://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1809.04281\n8. Khrennikov, A. (2010). Ubiquitous Quantum Structure: From Psychology to Finance.\nBerlin: Springer. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-05101-2\n9. Khrennikov, A. (2013). Quantum-like model of cognitive decision making and\ninformation processing. BioSystems, 112(2), 95–103.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.biosystems.2013.02.002\n10. Khrennikov, A. (2017). Why Quantum? In: Haven, E., Khrennikov, A. (eds) The\nPalgrave Handbook of Quantum Models in Social Science. Palgrave Macmillan,\nLondon. https://doi.org/10.1057/978-1-137-49276-0_15\n11. Busemeyer, J. R. and Bruza, P. D. (2012) Quantum Models of Cognition and\nDecision.\nCambridge: Cambridge University Press.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511997716\n12. Pothos, E. M. and Busemeyer, J. R. (2009)\nA quantum probability explanation for violations of ‘rational’ decision theory.\nProceedings of the Royal Society B, 276(1665), pp. 2171–2178.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1098/rspb.2009.0121\n13. Asano, M., Ohya, M., Tanaka, Y., Basieva, I. a Khrennikov, A. (2011). Quantum-like\nmodel of brain's functioning: Decision making from decoherence. Journal of\nTheoretical Biology, 281(1), s. 56–64. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jtbi.2011.04.022\n14. Kitto, K. (2008). Why Quantum Theory. Available at:\nhttps://api.semanticscholar.org/CorpusID:118817897\n\n\f", "numLines": 669, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 669}}}
